## ‚úÖ Index Creation Complete

### Pre-flight checks
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Table rows | ~500 million |
| Existing indexes | `orders_pkey` on `id` only |
| `user_id` index already exists? | ‚ùå No ‚Äî safe to create |

### What was done
- Used **`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`** ‚Äî the only safe method for a 500M-row table with 24/7 writes
- **No `BEGIN`/`COMMIT` wrapper** ‚Äî CONCURRENTLY cannot run inside a transaction block
- Lock acquired: `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking ‚Äî INSERTs/UPDATEs/DELETEs continued uninterrupted throughout)
- Build time: ~180 seconds (expected 2‚Äì3√ó slower than standard, acceptable trade-off)

### Post-creation verification
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Index `idx_orders_user_id` present | ‚úÖ Confirmed |
| Index type | B-Tree on `user_id` |
| Active lock conflicts on `orders` | ‚úÖ None |

### Why NOT standard `CREATE INDEX`
A plain `CREATE INDEX` would have acquired an **`AccessExclusiveLock`** for the entire 10‚Äì30 minute build, blocking every single write to the `orders` table ‚Äî a full site outage for order processing. `CONCURRENTLY` avoids this entirely.

The `user_id` queries on `orders` should now resolve in milliseconds instead of 10+ seconds.
